00:34:51,733 --> 00:34:54,771
shrimp burger, shrimp sandwich...

462
00:34:57,364 --> 00:34:59,697
That's... That's about it.

463
00:35:03,411 --> 00:35:06,370
<i>FORREST: Night time in the Army
is a lonely time.</i>

464
00:35:07,249 --> 00:35:10,868
<i>We'd lay there in our bunks
and I'd miss my mama.</i>

465
00:35:11,461 --> 00:35:13,953
<i>And I'd miss Jenny.</i>

466
00:35:17,884 --> 00:35:21,753
Hey, Gump, get a load of the tits on her!

467
00:35:35,235 --> 00:35:38,353
<i>Turns out, Jenny had gotten into
some trouble over</i>

468
00:35:38,446 --> 00:35:41,780
<i>some photos of her
in her college sweater,</i>

469
00:35:41,908 --> 00:35:44,446
<i>and she was thrown out of school.</i>

470
00:35:47,998 --> 00:35:50,206
<i>But that wasn't a bad thing,</i>

471
00:35:50,292 --> 00:35:53,876
<i>because a man who owns
a theater in Memphis, Tennessee,</i>

472
00:35:53,962 --> 00:35:59,003
<i>saw those photos and offered Jenny
a job singing in a show.</i>

473
00:35:59,801 --> 00:36:01,633
<i>The first chance I got,</i>

474
00:36:01,761 --> 00:36:05,425
<i>I took the bus up to Memphis
to see her perform in that show.</i>

475
00:36:05,515 --> 00:36:07,006
<i>That was Amber, Amber Flame.</i>

476
00:36:07,100 --> 00:36:09,558
<i>Give her a big hand, guys.
Good job, Amber.</i>

477
00:36:09,644 --> 00:36:12,387
<i>And now, for your listening
and viewing pleasure,</i>

478
00:36:12,480 --> 00:36:16,315
<i>direct from Hollywood, California,
our very own beatnik beauty,</i>

479
00:36:16,443 --> 00:36:20,107
<i>let's give a big round of applause
to the luscious Bobbi Dylan.</i>

480
00:36:20,363 --> 00:36:22,195
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

481
00:36:22,282 --> 00:36:24,524
MAN 1: All right!
MAN 2: Bobbi!

482
00:36:29,414 --> 00:36:34,079
(SINGING <i>BLOWIN' IN THE WIND)</i>

483
00:36:47,474 --> 00:36:49,557
<i>Her dream had come true.</i>

484
00:36:50,810 --> 00:36:52,802
<i>She was a folk singer.</i>

485
00:37:02,072 --> 00:37:04,314
MAN 3: Come on, baby. Shake it up.
Shake it up, now.

486
00:37:04,407 --> 00:37:05,967
MAN 4: Hey, buddy, get her a harmonica.

487
00:37:06,117 --> 00:37:07,699
(CROWD LAUGHING)

488
00:37:09,663 --> 00:37:11,700
MAN 1: Hey, honey,
this ain't <i>Captain Kangaroo.</i>

489
00:37:11,831 --> 00:37:14,369
Hey, honey,
I got something here for you.

490
00:37:15,418 --> 00:37:19,162
- God damn it!
- Hey! Hey! Stupid jerk!

491
00:37:19,256 --> 00:37:21,714
I'm singing a song here.

492
00:37:24,052 --> 00:37:26,465
Polly, get out here!

493
00:37:26,554 --> 00:37:28,324
- Shut up, there!
- MAN 2: Don't be so shy, honey.

494
00:37:28,348 --> 00:37:29,884
JENNY: Oh, shut up!

495
00:37:32,560 --> 00:37:35,303
Forrest, what are you doing here?

496
00:37:35,397 --> 00:37:37,104
- What are you doing?
- MAN 3: Hey!

497
00:37:37,190 --> 00:37:38,556
- Come on.
- What are you doing?

498
00:37:38,692 --> 00:37:40,684
Forrest, let me down!

499
00:37:42,028 --> 00:37:43,028
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

500
00:37:46,533 --> 00:37:48,445
You can't keep doing this, Forrest.

501
00:37:48,535 --> 00:37:50,618
You can't keep trying
to rescue me all the time.

502
00:37:50,704 --> 00:37:54,789
- They was trying to grab you.
- A lot of people try to grab me.

503
00:37:55,709 --> 00:37:58,873
Just... You can't keep
doing this all the time.

504
00:37:59,379 --> 00:38:02,292
I can't help it. I love you.

505
00:38:03,258 --> 00:38:06,751
Forrest, you don't know what love is.

506
00:38:14,060 --> 00:38:17,053
You remember that time
we prayed, Forrest?

507
00:38:17,939 --> 00:38:22,434
We prayed for God to turn me
into a bird so I could fly far, far away?

508
00:38:24,404 --> 00:38:25,770
Yes, I do.

509
00:38:29,743 --> 00:38:32,577
You think I could fly off this bridge?

510
00:38:39,252 --> 00:38:41,414
What do you mean, Jenny?

511
00:38:45,300 --> 00:38:46,791
Nothing.

512
00:38:49,763 --> 00:38:51,800
I gotta get out of here.

513
00:38:54,100 --> 00:38:55,181
Wait, Jenny...

514
00:38:55,268 --> 00:38:59,729
Forrest, you stay away from me, okay?
You just stay away from me, please.

515
00:38:59,814 --> 00:39:01,100
Can I have a ride?

516
00:39:01,191 --> 00:39:02,727
- MAN: Where you going?
- I don't care.

517
00:39:02,817 --> 00:39:04,183
Get in the truck.

518
00:39:04,277 --> 00:39:06,109
So, bye-bye, Jenny.

519
00:39:08,615 --> 00:39:10,948
They sending me to Vietnam.

520
00:39:13,703 --> 00:39:16,116
It's this whole other country.

521
00:39:18,625 --> 00:39:20,617
Just hang on a minute.

522
00:39:22,045 --> 00:39:25,083
Listen, you promise me
something, okay?

523
00:39:25,173 --> 00:39:28,507
Just, if you're ever in trouble,
don't try to be brave. You just run, okay?

524
00:39:28,635 --> 00:39:30,217
Just run away.

525
00:39:31,471 --> 00:39:32,803
Okay.

526
00:39:37,685 --> 00:39:39,017
Jenny.

527
00:39:40,897 --> 00:39:43,184
I'll write you all the time.

528
00:39:52,325 --> 00:39:55,318
<i>FORREST: And just like that,
she was gone.</i>

529
00:40:11,428 --> 00:40:14,762
You come back safe to me,
do you hear?

530
00:40:58,057 --> 00:41:02,017
<i>Now, they told us that Vietnam
was gonna be very different</i>

531
00:41:02,103 --> 00:41:04,971
<i>from the United States of America.</i>

532
00:41:05,064 --> 00:41:10,105
<i>And except for all the beer cans
and the barbecue, it was.</i>

533
00:41:20,246 --> 00:41:23,330
Hey, I bet there's shrimp
all in these waters.

534
00:41:23,416 --> 00:41:26,580
They tell me these Vietnams
is good shrimpers.

535
00:41:26,669 --> 00:41:30,208
You know, after we win this war,
and we take over everything,

536
00:41:30,298 --> 00:41:31,505
we can get American shrimpers

537
00:41:31,591 --> 00:41:33,332
to come out here
and shrimp these waters.

538
00:41:33,426 --> 00:41:34,962
We'll just shrimp all the time, man.

539
00:41:35,094 --> 00:41:38,258
So much shrimp, why,
you wouldn't believe it.

540
00:41:38,932 --> 00:41:40,844
You must be my FNGs.

541
00:41:40,934 --> 00:41:42,175
- Morning, sir!
- Morning, sir!

542
00:41:42,268 --> 00:41:44,885
Get your hands down! Do not salute me.

543
00:41:44,979 --> 00:41:47,096
There's goddamn snipers
all around this area

544
00:41:47,190 --> 00:41:50,024
who would love to grease an officer.

545
00:41:50,109 --> 00:41:53,602
I'm Lieutenant Dan Taylor.
Welcome to Fourth Platoon.

546
00:41:54,489 --> 00:41:56,902
What's wrong with your lip?

547
00:41:56,991 --> 00:41:59,358
I was born with big gums, sir.

548
00:41:59,452 --> 00:42:04,163
Yeah, well, you better tuck that in.
Gonna get that caught on a trip wire.

549
00:42:05,333 --> 00:42:06,699
Where you boys from in the world?

550
00:42:06,793 --> 00:42:09,160
- Alabama, sir!
- Alabama, sir!

551
00:42:09,879 --> 00:42:11,370
You twins?

552
00:42:13,466 --> 00:42:15,879
No, we are not relations, sir.

553
00:42:18,137 --> 00:42:21,050
Look, it's pretty basic here.

554
00:42:21,849 --> 00:42:24,307
If you stick with me
and learn from the guys

555
00:42:24,394 --> 00:42:27,057
who've been in country a while,
you'll be all right.

556
00:42:27,146 --> 00:42:29,058
There is one item of GI gear

557
00:42:29,148 --> 00:42:33,313
that can be the difference between
a live grunt and a dead grunt.

558
00:42:33,653 --> 00:42:36,817
Socks. Cushion sole, OD green.

559
00:42:36,906 --> 00:42:38,192
Try and keep your feet dry.

560
00:42:38,324 --> 00:42:39,802
When we're out humping,
I want you boys to remember

561
00:42:39,826 --> 00:42:42,284
to change your socks whenever we stop.

562
00:42:42,370 --> 00:42:45,329
The Mekong will eat a grunt's feet
right off his legs.

563
00:42:45,415 --> 00:42:47,702
Sergeant Sims, God damn it,

564
00:42:47,834 --> 00:42:49,311
where is that sling rope
I told you to order?

565
00:42:49,335 --> 00:42:51,247
I put in the requisitions at Battalion.

566
00:42:51,337 --> 00:42:53,399
DAN: Yeah, yeah, yeah, well,
you call those sons of bitches again...

567
00:42:53,423 --> 00:42:55,961
<i>FORREST: Lieutenant Dan
sure knew his stuff.</i>

568
00:42:56,050 --> 00:42:58,337
<i>I felt real lucky he was my lieutenant.</i>

569
00:42:59,095 --> 00:43:02,554
<i>He was from a long,
great military tradition.</i>

570
00:43:02,765 --> 00:43:05,849
<i>Somebody in his family
had fought and died</i>

571
00:43:06,853 --> 00:43:11,097
<i>in every single American war.</i>

572
00:43:12,025 --> 00:43:14,086
- God damn it, kick some ass!
- I'm on it, Lieutenant.

573
00:43:14,110 --> 00:43:15,226
Get on it!

574
00:43:15,361 --> 00:43:18,695
<i>I guess you could say he had
a lot to live up to.</i>

575
00:43:20,408 --> 00:43:25,244
So, you boys are from Arkansas, huh?
Well, I've been through there.

576
00:43:25,371 --> 00:43:27,533
Little Rock's a fine town.

577
00:43:28,207 --> 00:43:31,791
Now, go shake down your gear,
see the platoon sergeant,

578
00:43:31,878 --> 00:43:34,336
draw what you need for the field.

579
00:43:34,422 --> 00:43:38,382
If you boys are hungry,
we got steaks burning right over here.

580
00:43:38,468 --> 00:43:41,336
Two standing orders in this platoon:

581
00:43:41,429 --> 00:43:44,092
one, take good care of your feet,

582
00:43:44,223 --> 00:43:49,264
two, try not to do anything stupid,
like getting yourself killed.

583
00:43:55,735 --> 00:43:57,818
I sure hope I don't let him down.

584
00:44:09,415 --> 00:44:11,907
<i>FORREST: I got to see
a lot of the countryside.</i>

585
00:44:12,001 --> 00:44:14,334
<i>We would take these real long walks.</i>

586
00:44:22,804 --> 00:44:26,923
<i>And we were always looking
for this guy named Charlie.</i>

587
00:44:34,774 --> 00:44:37,016
DAN: Hold it up!
SOLDIER: Hold up, boys!

588
00:44:39,862 --> 00:44:42,195
<i>It wasn't always fun.</i>

589
00:44:42,281 --> 00:44:46,571
<i>Lieutenant Dan was always getting
these funny feelings about a rock,</i>

590
00:44:46,661 --> 00:44:51,747
<i>or a trail, or the road,
so he'd tell us to get down, shut up...</i>

591
00:44:51,833 --> 00:44:53,825
Get down! Shut up!

592
00:44:54,794 --> 00:44:56,251
<i>(WHISPERING)...so we did.</i>

593
00:45:13,813 --> 00:45:15,975
<i>Now, I don't know much about anything,</i>

594
00:45:16,065 --> 00:45:19,900
<i>but I think some of America's
best young men served in this war.</i>

595
00:45:19,986 --> 00:45:22,694
<i>There was Dallas, from Phoenix,</i>

596
00:45:24,407 --> 00:45:27,195
<i>Cleveland, he was from Detroit.</i>

597
00:45:27,326 --> 00:45:29,693
(WHISPERING) Hey, Tex. Hey, Tex.

598
00:45:29,829 --> 00:45:31,991
Man, what the hell's going on?

599
00:45:32,081 --> 00:45:36,416
<i>And Tex was... Well, I don't remember
where Tex come from.</i>

600
00:45:36,502 --> 00:45:38,038
DAN: Nothing.

601
00:45:42,175 --> 00:45:44,667
Fourth Platoon, on your feet.

602
00:45:44,761 --> 00:45:48,471
Still got 10 klicks to go to that river.
Move out.

603
00:45:48,556 --> 00:45:50,343
Come on, move out.

604
00:45:52,393 --> 00:45:54,806
Step it up. Look alive out there.

605
00:45:54,896 --> 00:45:59,231
<i>The good thing about Vietnam
is there was always some place to go.</i>

606
00:45:59,358 --> 00:46:00,724
DAN: Fire in the hole!

607
00:46:04,197 --> 00:46:06,530
Gump, check out that hole.

608
00:46:06,616 --> 00:46:09,609
<i>And there was always something to do.</i>

609
00:46:09,702 --> 00:46:12,866
- Mount them up.
- SOLDIER: Spread out! Cover his back.

610
00:46:17,919 --> 00:46:23,540
<i>One day, it started raining,
and it didn't quit for four months.</i>

611
00:46:24,550 --> 00:46:27,418
<i>We'd been through
every kind of rain there is:</i>

612
00:46:27,553 --> 00:46:30,091
<i>little bitty stinging rain,</i>

613
00:46:30,807 --> 00:46:33,470
<i>and big old fat rain,</i>

614
00:46:33,935 --> 00:46:36,643
<i>rain that flew in sideways.</i>

615
00:46:36,729 --> 00:46:40,769
<i>And sometimes, rain even seemed
to come straight up from underneath.</i>

616
00:46:42,568 --> 00:46:44,935
<i>Shoot, it even rained at night.</i>

617
00:46:45,988 --> 00:46:48,446
- Hey, Forrest.
- Hey, Bubba.

618
00:46:48,574 --> 00:46:51,863
I'm gonna lean up against you.
You just lean right back against me.

619
00:46:51,953 --> 00:46:55,788
This way, we don't have to sleep
with our heads in the mud.

620
00:46:56,749 --> 00:47:00,208
You know why we a good partnership,
Forrest?

621
00:47:00,294 --> 00:47:02,786
'Cause we be watching out
for one another,

622
00:47:02,922 --> 00:47:04,788
like brothers and stuff.

623
00:47:06,759 --> 00:47:10,423
Hey, Forrest, there's something
I've been thinking about.

624
00:47:10,513 --> 00:47:13,506
I got a very important question
to ask you.

625
00:47:15,142 --> 00:47:19,102
How would you like to go
into the shrimping business with me?

626
00:47:20,273 --> 00:47:21,889
Okay.

627
00:47:21,983 --> 00:47:25,442
Man, I tell you what,
I got it all figured out, too.

628
00:47:25,528 --> 00:47:28,316
So many pounds of shrimp
to pay off the boat,

629
00:47:28,447 --> 00:47:31,736
so many pounds for gas,
we can just live right on the boat.

630
00:47:31,826 --> 00:47:34,113
We ain't got to pay no rent.

631
00:47:34,203 --> 00:47:36,286
I'll be the captain,
we can just work it together,

632
00:47:36,372 --> 00:47:40,616
split everything right down the middle.
Man, I'm telling you, 50-50.

633
00:47:40,710 --> 00:47:44,294
And, hey, Forrest,
all the shrimp you can eat.

634
00:47:45,840 --> 00:47:47,627
That's a fine idea.

635
00:47:48,718 --> 00:47:50,835
<i>FORREST: Bubba did have a fine idea.</i>

636
00:47:54,640 --> 00:47:57,724
<i>I even wrote Jenny
and told her all about it.</i>

637
00:47:58,519 --> 00:48:01,728
<i>I sent her letters,
not every day, but almost.</i>

638
00:48:01,814 --> 00:48:06,809
<i>I told her what I was doing
and asked her what she was doing,</i>

639
00:48:06,903 --> 00:48:09,646
<i>and told her
how I thought about her always,</i>

640
00:48:10,990 --> 00:48:13,949
<i>and how I was looking forward
to getting a letter from her</i>

641
00:48:14,035 --> 00:48:16,527
<i>just as soon as she had the time.</i>

642
00:48:18,414 --> 00:48:20,906
<i>I'd always let her know that I was okay.</i>

643
00:48:22,209 --> 00:48:27,375
<i>Then, I'd sign each letter,
"Love, Forrest Gump."</i>

644
00:48:42,229 --> 00:48:45,973
<i>This one day, we was out walking,
like always,</i>

645
00:48:46,067 --> 00:48:49,026
<i>and then, just like that,</i>

646
00:48:49,946 --> 00:48:53,360
<i>somebody turned off the rain
and the sun come out.</i>

647
00:48:56,369 --> 00:48:58,201
DAN: Ambush!

648
00:48:58,704 --> 00:49:00,070
Take cover!

649
00:49:00,247 --> 00:49:01,613
(GUNS FIRING)

650
00:49:03,709 --> 00:49:04,870
Get down!

651
00:49:04,961 --> 00:49:06,418
Get the sixty!

652
00:49:09,590 --> 00:49:11,673
Get that pig up here, God damn it!

653
00:49:11,759 --> 00:49:13,876
Forrest, you okay?

654
00:49:17,098 --> 00:49:19,715
Strongarm! Strongarm!
Be advised, Strongarm!

655
00:49:20,267 --> 00:49:22,680
Medic, we got a man down!

656
00:49:22,770 --> 00:49:25,729
Strongarm, this is Leg Lima 6, over!

657
00:49:26,440 --> 00:49:29,774
Roger, Strongarm, be advised
we have incoming from the tree line

658
00:49:29,902 --> 00:49:33,395
at points blue plus two.
AKs and rockets...

659
00:49:34,073 --> 00:49:35,860
Misfire! Misfire!

660
00:49:38,244 --> 00:49:40,236
DAN: God damn it! Mac!

661
00:49:41,205 --> 00:49:44,619
Get that thing...
Fuck it, get it in the tree line!

662
00:49:45,584 --> 00:49:46,745
Jesus!

663
00:49:46,877 --> 00:49:49,085
My unit is down hard and hurting!

664
00:49:49,213 --> 00:49:52,752
Six are pulling back to Blue Line,
Leg Lima 6 out.

665
00:49:53,551 --> 00:49:55,508
Pull back! Pull back!

666
00:49:55,594 --> 00:49:57,711
Run! Run, Forrest!

667
00:49:57,805 --> 00:50:00,138
- Pull back!
- BUBBA: Forrest, Forrest!

668
00:50:00,266 --> 00:50:02,849
Run, man! Run!

669
00:50:02,935 --> 00:50:04,722
DAN: Pull back! Run!

670
00:50:06,564 --> 00:50:08,772
Run, God damn it, run!

671
00:50:29,962 --> 00:50:34,582
SOLDIER: Medic! Can I get a medic?

672
00:50:34,967 --> 00:50:38,301
<i>FORREST: I ran and ran,
just like Jenny told me to.</i>

673
00:50:41,682 --> 00:50:45,892
<i>I ran so far and so fast
that pretty soon I was all by myself,</i>

674
00:50:45,978 --> 00:50:47,935
<i>which was a bad thing.</i>

675
00:50:48,481 --> 00:50:50,017
Bubba!

676
00:50:52,151 --> 00:50:55,940
<i>Bubba was my best good friend.
I had to make sure that he was okay.</i>

677
00:50:59,658 --> 00:51:01,695
SOLDIER 1: Any friendlies out there?

678
00:51:02,661 --> 00:51:04,823
SOLDIER 2: Yeah, I've got
three over here.

679
00:51:05,456 --> 00:51:07,448
Where the hell are you?

680
00:51:08,042 --> 00:51:09,374
Bubba?

681
00:51:10,461 --> 00:51:13,169
<i>And on my way back to find Bubba,</i>

682
00:51:13,297 --> 00:51:16,085
<i>well, there was this boy
laying on the ground.</i>

683
00:51:16,175 --> 00:51:17,382
Tex!

684
00:51:19,470 --> 00:51:20,470
Okay.

685
00:51:20,554 --> 00:51:24,514
<i>I couldn't just let him lay there
all alone, scared the way he was,</i>

686
00:51:24,642 --> 00:51:28,511
<i>so I grabbed him up
and run him out of there.</i>

687
00:51:43,661 --> 00:51:46,074
<i>And every time I went back
looking for Bubba,</i>

688
00:51:46,205 --> 00:51:49,698
<i>somebody else was saying,
"Help me, Forrest. Help me."</i>

689
00:51:57,383 --> 00:51:59,249
Can't hear... Can't hear...

690
00:52:01,554 --> 00:52:02,906
SOLDIER: No sweat, man. Just lay back.

691
00:52:02,930 --> 00:52:05,422
You'll be okay. You'll be okay.

692
