1148
01:26:33,665 --> 01:26:35,907
<i>and I always try to keep my promise.</i>

1149
01:26:36,001 --> 01:26:37,537
<i>So, I went on down to Bayou La Batre</i>

1150
01:26:37,628 --> 01:26:41,372
<i>to meet Bubba's family
and make their introduction.</i>

1151
01:26:41,465 --> 01:26:45,129
Are you crazy, or just plain stupid?

1152
01:26:45,844 --> 01:26:48,086
Stupid is as stupid does, Mrs. Blue.

1153
01:26:48,180 --> 01:26:49,546
I guess.

1154
01:26:50,557 --> 01:26:54,141
<i>And, of course,
I paid my respect to Bubba himself.</i>

1155
01:26:56,146 --> 01:26:58,684
Hey, Bubba, it's me, Forrest Gump.

1156
01:27:01,818 --> 01:27:05,858
I remember everything you said,
and I got it all figured out.

1157
01:27:08,659 --> 01:27:15,452
I'm taking the $24,562
and 47 cents that I got...

1158
01:27:16,541 --> 01:27:20,125
<i>Or, that's left after a new hair cut
and a new suit,</i>

1159
01:27:20,212 --> 01:27:22,169
<i>and I took Mama out
to a real fancy dinner,</i>

1160
01:27:22,256 --> 01:27:25,499
<i>and I bought a bus ticket
and three Dr. Peppers.</i>

1161
01:27:26,051 --> 01:27:27,838
Tell me something.

1162
01:27:28,887 --> 01:27:31,004
SHRIMPER: Are you stupid
or something?

1163
01:27:31,098 --> 01:27:33,135
Stupid is as stupid does, sir.

1164
01:27:33,225 --> 01:27:36,184
Well, that's what's left after me saying,

1165
01:27:37,104 --> 01:27:39,264
"When I was in China
on the All-America Ping-Pong team,

1166
01:27:39,356 --> 01:27:43,145
"I just loved playing Ping-Pong with
my Flex-O-Light Ping-Pong paddle,"

1167
01:27:43,235 --> 01:27:44,545
which everybody knows isn't true,

1168
01:27:44,569 --> 01:27:46,005
but Mama says it's just a little white lie

1169
01:27:46,029 --> 01:27:48,191
so it wouldn't hurt nobody.

1170
01:27:49,616 --> 01:27:55,533
So, anyway, I'm putting all that on gas,
ropes and new nets

1171
01:27:56,290 --> 01:27:58,031
and a brand-new shrimping boat.

1172
01:28:19,730 --> 01:28:22,973
<i>Now, Bubba had told me everything
he knew about shrimping,</i>

1173
01:28:23,066 --> 01:28:25,399
<i>but you know what I found out?</i>

1174
01:28:27,070 --> 01:28:29,403
<i>Shrimping is tough.</i>

1175
01:28:31,616 --> 01:28:33,448
I only caught five.

1176
01:28:33,577 --> 01:28:35,471
A couple more,
you could have yourself a cocktail.

1177
01:28:35,495 --> 01:28:36,576
(CHUCKLING)

1178
01:28:40,250 --> 01:28:42,061
Hey, you ever think
about naming this old boat?

1179
01:28:42,085 --> 01:28:44,748
It's bad luck
to have a boat without a name.

1180
01:28:47,132 --> 01:28:51,968
<i>I'd never named a boat before,
but there was only one I could think of,</i>

1181
01:28:53,138 --> 01:28:56,347
<i>the most beautiful name
in the wide world.</i>

1182
01:29:00,687 --> 01:29:03,896
<i>(GETDOWN TONIGHT</i> PLAYING)

1183
01:29:17,371 --> 01:29:20,205
<i>Now, I hadn't heard from Jenny
in a long while,</i>

1184
01:29:20,290 --> 01:29:22,828
<i>but I thought about her a lot,</i>

1185
01:29:22,959 --> 01:29:26,418
<i>and I hoped that whatever
she was doing made her happy.</i>

1186
01:31:12,694 --> 01:31:15,232
<i>I thought about Jenny all the time.</i>

1187
01:31:34,758 --> 01:31:35,758
(LAUGHS)

1188
01:31:39,888 --> 01:31:41,049
Hey!

1189
01:32:04,913 --> 01:32:09,578
Lieutenant Dan,
what are you doing here?

1190
01:32:09,668 --> 01:32:13,582
Well, thought I'd try out my sea legs.

1191
01:32:13,672 --> 01:32:17,416
But you ain't got no legs,
Lieutenant Dan.

1192
01:32:17,509 --> 01:32:19,796
Yes, I know that.

1193
01:32:20,136 --> 01:32:22,173
You wrote me a letter, you idiot.

1194
01:32:22,305 --> 01:32:26,845
Well, well. Captain Forrest Gump.
I had to see this for myself.

1195
01:32:28,478 --> 01:32:35,351
And I told you if you were ever
a shrimp boat captain

1196
01:32:35,485 --> 01:32:38,068
that I'd be your first mate.
Well, here I am.

1197
01:32:38,154 --> 01:32:41,272
- I am a man of my word.
- Okay.

1198
01:32:41,366 --> 01:32:45,360
Yeah, but don't you be thinking that
I'm going to be calling you "sir."

1199
01:32:45,495 --> 01:32:46,827
No, sir.

1200
01:32:55,714 --> 01:32:58,001
That's my boat.

1201
01:33:00,594 --> 01:33:06,056
DAN: I have a feeling if we head
due east, we'll find some shrimp,

1202
01:33:06,182 --> 01:33:07,764
so take a left.

1203
01:33:09,185 --> 01:33:12,098
- Take a left!
- Which way?

1204
01:33:12,188 --> 01:33:14,851
Over there! They're over there!

1205
01:33:15,525 --> 01:33:19,360
- Get on the wheel and take a left!
- Okay.

1206
01:33:20,572 --> 01:33:24,691
Gump, what are you doing?
Take a left! Left!

1207
01:33:27,078 --> 01:33:30,697
That's where we're going
to find those shrimp, my boy!

1208
01:33:32,292 --> 01:33:33,874
That's where we'll find them.

1209
01:33:46,556 --> 01:33:50,675
- Still no shrimp, Lieutenant Dan.
- Okay, so I was wrong.

1210
01:33:51,394 --> 01:33:54,603
How are we going to find them?

1211
01:33:54,731 --> 01:33:57,223
Well, maybe you should
just pray for shrimp.

1212
01:33:57,942 --> 01:34:00,935
(SINGING GOSPEL MUSIC)

1213
01:34:03,865 --> 01:34:06,528
<i>FORREST:
So, I went to church every Sunday.</i>

1214
01:34:07,786 --> 01:34:09,778
<i>Sometimes Lieutenant Dan came, too,</i>

1215
01:34:09,913 --> 01:34:12,906
<i>though I think
he left the praying up to me.</i>

1216
01:34:28,390 --> 01:34:32,760
- No shrimp.
- Where the hell's this God of yours?

1217
01:34:33,603 --> 01:34:39,315
<i>It's funny Lieutenant Dan said that,
'cause right then, God showed up.</i>

1218
01:34:56,167 --> 01:35:01,003
- DAN: You'll never sink this boat!
<i>- Now, me, I was scared,</i>

1219
01:35:01,131 --> 01:35:04,169
<i>but Lieutenant Dan, he was mad.</i>

1220
01:35:04,300 --> 01:35:05,632
Come on!

1221
01:35:08,763 --> 01:35:13,975
You call this a storm?
Come on, you son of a bitch!

1222
01:35:16,104 --> 01:35:20,474
It's time for a showdown! You and me!

1223
01:35:20,608 --> 01:35:24,477
I'm right here! Come and get me!

1224
01:35:24,571 --> 01:35:26,153
(CACKLING)

1225
01:35:26,281 --> 01:35:30,150
You'll never sink this boat!

1226
01:35:32,203 --> 01:35:34,365
<i>Hurricane Carmen
came through here yesterday,</i>

1227
01:35:34,497 --> 01:35:37,035
<i>destroying nearly everything in its path.</i>

1228
01:35:37,167 --> 01:35:39,659
<i>And as in other towns
up and down the coast,</i>

1229
01:35:39,836 --> 01:35:42,203
<i>Bayou La Batre's
entire shrimping industry</i>

1230
01:35:42,297 --> 01:35:46,166
<i>has fallen victim to Carmen
and has been left in utter ruin.</i>

1231
01:35:46,301 --> 01:35:49,419
<i>Speaking with local officials,
this reporter has learned,</i>

1232
01:35:49,512 --> 01:35:52,971
<i>in fact, only one shrimping boat
actually survived the storm.</i>

1233
01:35:53,349 --> 01:35:55,966
Louise. Louise, there's Forrest.

1234
01:35:56,686 --> 01:35:58,678
<i>FORREST: After that,
shrimping was easy.</i>

1235
01:36:04,360 --> 01:36:07,478
<i>Since people still needed
them shrimps for shrimp cocktails</i>

1236
01:36:07,572 --> 01:36:11,691
and barbecues and all,
and we were the only boat left standing,

1237
01:36:11,868 --> 01:36:15,111
Bubba-Gump Shrimp's what they got.

1238
01:36:15,205 --> 01:36:19,791
We got a whole bunch of boats,
12 <i>Jennys,</i>

1239
01:36:19,876 --> 01:36:23,369
a big old warehouse. We even have
hats that say "Bubba-Gump" on them.

1240
01:36:23,713 --> 01:36:27,002
Bubba-Gump Shrimp.
It's a household name.

1241
01:36:27,217 --> 01:36:28,924
Hold on there, boy.

1242
01:36:29,052 --> 01:36:33,592
Are you telling me you're the owner of
the Bubba-Gump Shrimp Corporation?

1243
01:36:33,723 --> 01:36:36,716
Yes, sir. We got more money
than Davy Crockett.

1244
01:36:36,810 --> 01:36:38,267
(LAUGHING)

1245
01:36:38,353 --> 01:36:42,393
Boy, I heard some whoppers in my time,
but that tops them all.

1246
01:36:45,109 --> 01:36:47,897
We was sitting next to a millionaire.

1247
01:36:51,407 --> 01:36:56,027
Well, I thought it was a very lovely story,

1248
01:36:56,454 --> 01:37:01,074
and you tell it so well,
with such enthusiasm.

1249
01:37:02,794 --> 01:37:05,457
Would you like to see
what Lieutenant Dan looks like?

1250
01:37:05,588 --> 01:37:07,079
Well, yes, I would.

1251
01:37:12,095 --> 01:37:14,132
That's him right there.

1252
01:37:16,474 --> 01:37:18,716
And let me tell you something
about Lieutenant Dan...

1253
01:37:19,894 --> 01:37:20,930
Forrest,

1254
01:37:26,484 --> 01:37:29,272
I never thanked you for saving my life.

1255
01:37:55,305 --> 01:38:01,597
<i>FORREST: He never actually said so,
but I think he made his peace with God.</i>

1256
01:38:07,483 --> 01:38:08,974
<i>(GUNSHOTS FIRING)</i>

1257
01:38:09,277 --> 01:38:11,485
<i>For the second time in 17 days,</i>

1258
01:38:11,613 --> 01:38:15,072
<i>President Ford escaped
possible assassination today.</i>

1259
01:38:15,158 --> 01:38:16,444
<i>MARGO: Base to</i> Jenny 1.

1260
01:38:16,534 --> 01:38:20,027
<i>- Base to</i> Jenny 1.
<i>- Jenny 1</i>. Go, Margo.

1261
01:38:20,121 --> 01:38:21,612
<i>Forrest has a phone call.</i>

1262
01:38:21,706 --> 01:38:24,198
Yeah, well, you'll have to tell them
to call him back.

1263
01:38:24,292 --> 01:38:27,660
- He is indisposed at the moment.
<i>- His mama's sick.</i>

1264
01:38:48,358 --> 01:38:50,725
- Where's Mama?
- She's upstairs.

1265
01:38:53,571 --> 01:38:55,528
Hi, Forrest.

1266
01:38:56,491 --> 01:38:59,029
- DOCTOR: I'll see you tomorrow.
- All right.

1267
01:39:05,708 --> 01:39:08,872
We sure got you straightened out,
didn't we, boy?

1268
01:39:20,223 --> 01:39:24,183
- What's the matter, Mama?
- I'm dying, Forrest.

1269
01:39:27,522 --> 01:39:29,889
Come on in, sit down over here.

1270
01:39:44,247 --> 01:39:47,740
- Why are you dying, Mama?
- It's my time.

1271
01:39:48,751 --> 01:39:50,617
It's just my time.

1272
01:39:52,088 --> 01:39:56,253
Now, don't you be afraid, sweetheart.

1273
01:39:57,885 --> 01:40:00,252
Death is just a part of life,

1274
01:40:01,264 --> 01:40:03,881
something we're all destined to do.

1275
01:40:05,727 --> 01:40:10,097
I didn't know it,
but I was destined to be your mama.

1276
01:40:10,940 --> 01:40:14,524
- I did the best I could.
- You did good, Mama.

1277
01:40:15,319 --> 01:40:20,485
Well, I happen to believe
you make your own destiny.

1278
01:40:21,993 --> 01:40:25,236
You have to do the best
with what God gave you.

1279
01:40:29,125 --> 01:40:31,242
What's my destiny, Mama?

1280
01:40:33,421 --> 01:40:36,630
You're going to have
to figure that out for yourself.

1281
01:40:37,925 --> 01:40:40,884
Life is a box of chocolates, Forrest.

1282
01:40:40,970 --> 01:40:43,132
You never know
what you're going to get.

1283
01:40:43,264 --> 01:40:47,634
<i>Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.</i>

1284
01:40:47,727 --> 01:40:49,935
I will miss you, Forrest.

1285
01:40:51,773 --> 01:40:55,813
<i>She had got the cancer
and died on a Tuesday.</i>

1286
01:40:57,320 --> 01:41:00,654
<i>I bought her a new hat
with little flowers on it.</i>

1287
01:41:03,701 --> 01:41:06,990
And that's all I have to say about that.

1288
01:41:13,836 --> 01:41:16,123
Didn't you say you were waiting
for the number seven bus?

1289
01:41:16,214 --> 01:41:19,002
There'll be another one along shortly.

1290
01:41:22,845 --> 01:41:26,429
Now, because I had been a football star,
and a war hero,

1291
01:41:26,516 --> 01:41:29,634
and a national celebrity,
and a shrimping boat captain,

1292
01:41:30,144 --> 01:41:33,353
and a college graduate,
the city fathers of Greenbow, Alabama

1293
01:41:33,481 --> 01:41:36,690
decided to get together
and offered me a fine job.

1294
01:41:38,069 --> 01:41:41,733
<i>So, I never went back to work
for Lieutenant Dan,</i>

1295
01:41:41,864 --> 01:41:44,572
<i>though he did take care
of my Bubba-Gump money.</i>

1296
01:41:44,700 --> 01:41:49,286
<i>He got me invested
in some kind of fruit company.</i>

1297
01:41:49,372 --> 01:41:51,012
<i>And so then, I got a call from him saying</i>

1298
01:41:51,040 --> 01:41:54,499
we don't have to worry about money
no more, and I said,

1299
01:41:54,585 --> 01:41:56,872
"That's good. One less thing."

1300
01:41:57,380 --> 01:41:59,497
(SINGING GOSPEL MUSIC)

1301
01:41:59,924 --> 01:42:03,838
<i>Now, Mama said there's only
so much fortune a man really needs,</i>

1302
01:42:04,595 --> 01:42:07,429
<i>and the rest is just for showing off.</i>

1303
01:42:07,515 --> 01:42:11,384
<i>So, I gave a whole bunch of it
to the Foursquare gospel church,</i>

1304
01:42:13,855 --> 01:42:18,020
<i>and I gave a whole bunch to the
Bayou La Batre fishing hospital.</i>

1305
01:42:20,903 --> 01:42:25,443
<i>And even though Bubba was dead
and Lieutenant Dan said I was nuts,</i>

1306
01:42:25,575 --> 01:42:28,192
<i>I gave Bubba's mama Bubba's share.</i>

1307
01:42:32,415 --> 01:42:34,122
You know what?

1308
01:42:35,376 --> 01:42:38,369
<i>She didn't have to work
in nobody's kitchen no more.</i>

1309
01:42:38,462 --> 01:42:40,078
That smells wonderful.

1310
01:42:40,923 --> 01:42:44,837
<i>And 'cause I was a gazillionaire
and I liked doing it so much,</i>

1311
01:42:44,927 --> 01:42:47,260
<i>I cut that grass for free.</i>

1312
01:42:51,058 --> 01:42:53,926
<i>But at night time
when there was nothing to do</i>

1313
01:42:54,020 --> 01:42:56,387
<i>and the house was all empty,</i>

1314
01:42:57,398 --> 01:42:59,765
<i>I'd always think of Jenny.</i>

1315
01:44:03,464 --> 01:44:06,628
<i>And then, she was there.</i>

1316
01:44:39,625 --> 01:44:42,789
- Hello, Forrest.
- Hello, Jenny.

1317
01:44:54,348 --> 01:44:56,965
<i>Jenny came back and stayed with me.</i>

1318
01:44:58,561 --> 01:45:02,225
<i>Maybe it was because
she had nowhere else to go,</i>

1319
01:45:02,356 --> 01:45:06,066
<i>or maybe it was because she was
so tired, 'cause she went to bed</i>

1320
01:45:06,193 --> 01:45:10,153
<i>and slept and slept,
like she hadn't slept in years.</i>

1321
01:45:11,407 --> 01:45:13,694
<i>It was wonderful having her home.</i>

1322
01:45:15,036 --> 01:45:20,156
<i>Every day we'd take a walk and
I'd jabber on like a monkey in a tree,</i>

1323
01:45:20,249 --> 01:45:22,787
<i>and she'd listen about Ping-Ponging,
and shrimping,</i>

1324
01:45:22,877 --> 01:45:27,167
<i>and Mama making a trip up to heaven.
I did all the talking.</i>

1325
01:45:27,256 --> 01:45:30,590
<i>Jenny most of the time was real quiet.</i>

1326
01:46:10,758 --> 01:46:13,967
How could you do this?

1327
01:46:27,274 --> 01:46:29,266
(CRYING)

1328
01:46:50,923 --> 01:46:54,257
<i>Sometimes I guess there
just aren't enough rocks.</i>

1329
01:46:56,470 --> 01:47:00,965
<i>I never really knew why she came back,
but I didn't care.</i>

1330
01:47:01,142 --> 01:47:05,432
<i>It was like olden times.
We was like peas and carrots again.</i>

1331
01:47:07,523 --> 01:47:11,858
<i>Every day, I'd pick pretty flowers
and put them in her room for her,</i>

1332
01:47:13,362 --> 01:47:16,946
<i>and she gave me the best gift anyone
could ever get in the wide world.</i>

1333
01:47:17,032 --> 01:47:19,866
- New shoes.
- They make them just for running.

1334
01:47:24,874 --> 01:47:28,163
<i>And she even showed me how to dance.</i>

1335
01:47:36,343 --> 01:47:40,553
<i>And, well, we was like family,
Jenny and me.</i>

1336
01:47:44,310 --> 01:47:47,223
<i>And it was the happiest time in my life.</i>

1337
01:48:06,874 --> 01:48:08,727
<i>MAN ON TV:...and this Fourth is
witnessing one of the</i>

1338
01:48:08,751 --> 01:48:11,744
<i>largest fireworks displays
in the nation's...</i>

1339
01:48:11,837 --> 01:48:14,750
- You done watching it?
<i>- ...here in New York Harbor...</i>

1340
01:48:14,882 --> 01:48:16,735
- I'm going to bed.
<i>- ...with a spectacular display</i>

1341
01:48:16,759 --> 01:48:19,797
<i>of tall ships earlier.
The Statue of Liberty...</i>

1342
01:48:26,852 --> 01:48:28,844
Will you marry me?

1343
01:48:33,776 --> 01:48:36,735
I'd make a good husband, Jenny.

1344
01:48:39,406 --> 01:48:41,443
You would, Forrest.

1345
01:48:43,285 --> 01:48:45,618
But you won't marry me.

1346
01:48:47,915 --> 01:48:50,123
You don't want to marry me.

1347
01:48:53,712 --> 01:48:56,125
Why don't you love me, Jenny?

1348
01:49:01,136 --> 01:49:03,253
I'm not a smart man,

1349
01:49:04,974 --> 01:49:07,387
but I know what love is.

1350
01:49:44,430 --> 01:49:45,671
Jenny.

1351
01:49:47,600 --> 01:49:50,092
Forrest, I do love you.

1352
01:50:43,238 --> 01:50:46,902
- Where are you running off to?
- I'm not running.

1353
01:52:18,500 --> 01:52:23,837
<i>That day, for no particular reason,
I decided to go for a little run.</i>

1354
01:52:25,007 --> 01:52:29,422
<i>So, I ran to the end of the road,
and when I got there,</i>

1355
01:52:29,511 --> 01:52:31,252
<i>I thought maybe I'd run
to the end of town.</i>

1356
01:52:31,346 --> 01:52:32,574
<i>REPORTER: President Carter, suffering</i>

1357
01:52:32,598 --> 01:52:34,590
<i>from heat exhaustion,
fell into the arms of...</i>

1358
01:52:34,683 --> 01:52:36,345
<i>FORREST: And when I got there,</i>

1359
01:52:36,435 --> 01:52:40,600
<i>I thought maybe I'd just
run across Greenbow County.</i>

1360
01:52:40,689 --> 01:52:43,102
<i>And I figured since I'd run this far,</i>

1361
01:52:43,192 --> 01:52:46,435
<i>maybe I'd just run across
the great state of Alabama.</i>

1362
01:52:46,528 --> 01:52:47,735
<i>And that's what I did.</i>

1363
01:52:48,363 --> 01:52:50,946
I ran clear across Alabama.

1364
01:52:51,200 --> 01:52:54,364
For no particular reason,
I just kept on going.

1365
01:52:55,704 --> 01:52:57,286
I ran clear to the ocean.

1366
01:53:03,170 --> 01:53:06,334
<i>And when I got there,
I figured since I'd gone this far,</i>

1367
01:53:06,882 --> 01:53:09,716
<i>might as well turn around
and just keep on going.</i>

1368
01:53:13,472 --> 01:53:18,058
<i>And when I got to another ocean,
I figured since I'd gone this far,</i>

1369
01:53:19,853 --> 01:53:23,563
<i>I might as well just turn back
and keep right on going.</i>

1370
01:53:24,733 --> 01:53:29,569
<i>When I got tired, I slept.
When I got hungry, I ate.</i>

1371
01:53:29,655 --> 01:53:32,693
When I had to go, you know...

1372
01:53:34,326 --> 01:53:35,487
I went.

1373
01:53:35,577 --> 01:53:38,570
And so, you just ran.

1374
01:53:40,332 --> 01:53:41,413
Yeah.

1375
01:53:41,500 --> 01:53:44,243
<i>(RUNNING ON EMPTY</i> PLAYING)

1376
01:54:16,702 --> 01:54:21,948
<i>FORREST: I'd think a lot about Mama
and Bubba and Lieutenant Dan.</i>

1377
01:54:22,958 --> 01:54:26,451
<i>But most of all, I thought about Jenny.</i>

1378
01:54:27,546 --> 01:54:29,708
<i>I thought about her a lot.</i>

1379
01:54:30,465 --> 01:54:33,549
<i>For more than two years now,
a man named Forrest Gump,</i>

1380
01:54:33,635 --> 01:54:37,049
<i>a gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,
stopping only to sleep,</i>

1381
01:54:37,139 --> 01:54:39,301
<i>has been running across America.</i>

1382
01:54:39,391 --> 01:54:41,383
<i>Charles Cooper brings us this report.</i>

1383
01:54:42,311 --> 01:54:44,724
<i>For the fourth time
on his journey across America,</i>

1384
01:54:44,813 --> 01:54:47,647
<i>Forrest Gump,
the gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,</i>

1385
01:54:47,774 --> 01:54:50,642
<i>is about to cross
the Mississippi River again today.</i>

1386
01:54:51,278 --> 01:54:53,381
- I'll be damned. Forrest?
<i>- Sir, why are you running?</i>

1387
01:54:53,405 --> 01:54:54,486
Why are you running?

1388
01:54:54,573 --> 01:54:56,155
Are you doing this for world peace?

1389
01:54:56,241 --> 01:54:57,635
Are you doing this for the homeless?

1390
01:54:57,659 --> 01:55:00,652
- Are you running for women's rights?
- Or for the environment?

1391
01:55:00,746 --> 01:55:01,746
Or for animals?

1392
01:55:01,830 --> 01:55:04,790
<i>FORREST: They just couldn't believe
that somebody would do all that running</i>

1393
01:55:04,833 --> 01:55:06,199
<i>for no particular reason.</i>

1394
01:55:06,293 --> 01:55:08,250
REPORTER: Why are you doing this?

1395
01:55:08,337 --> 01:55:10,829
I just felt like running.

1396
01:55:10,964 --> 01:55:13,331
I just felt like running.

1397
01:55:13,467 --> 01:55:16,676
It's you. I can't believe it's really you.

1398
01:55:17,512 --> 01:55:22,632
Now, for some reason, what I was doing
seemed to make sense to people.

1399
01:55:22,809 --> 01:55:24,996
I mean, it was like an alarm
went off in my head, you know?

1400
01:55:25,020 --> 01:55:26,956
I said,
"Here's a guy that's got his act together.

1401
01:55:26,980 --> 01:55:28,937
"Here's somebody
who's got it all figured out.

1402
01:55:29,024 --> 01:55:33,109
"Here's somebody who has the answer."
I'll follow you anywhere, Mr. Gump.

1403
01:55:33,195 --> 01:55:35,027
<i>So, I got company.</i>

1404
01:55:36,865 --> 01:55:42,702
<i>And after that, I got more company.
And then, even more people joined in.</i>

1405
01:55:45,165 --> 01:55:48,374
Somebody later told me
it gave people hope.

1406
01:55:50,170 --> 01:55:53,538
Now... Now, I don't know
anything about that,

1407
01:55:54,383 --> 01:55:56,966
<i>but some of those people
asked me if I could help them out.</i>

1408
01:55:57,177 --> 01:56:00,420
Hey, man, hey, listen, I was wondering
if you might help me, huh?

1409
01:56:00,514 --> 01:56:02,255
Listen, I'm in the
bumper sticker business

1410
01:56:02,349 --> 01:56:04,160
and I've been trying
to think up a good slogan.

1411
01:56:04,184 --> 01:56:07,302
And since you have been such a big
inspiration to the people around here,

1412
01:56:07,396 --> 01:56:09,374
I thought you might
be able to help me jump into...

1413
01:56:09,398 --> 01:56:13,017
Whoa, man! You just ran through
a big pile of dog shit!

1414
01:56:14,569 --> 01:56:17,232
- It happens.
- What, shit?

1415
01:56:18,740 --> 01:56:20,697
Sometimes.

1416
01:56:22,577 --> 01:56:25,240
<i>And some years later,
I heard that that fellow</i>

1417
01:56:25,330 --> 01:56:27,162
<i>did come up with
a bumper sticker slogan,</i>

1418
01:56:27,249 --> 01:56:30,242
<i>and he made a lot of money off of it.</i>

1419
01:56:31,712 --> 01:56:33,920
<i>Another time, I was running along,</i>

1420
01:56:34,047 --> 01:56:37,336
<i>somebody who had lost all his money
in the T-shirt business,</i>

1421
01:56:37,426 --> 01:56:39,463
<i>he wanted to put my face on a T-shirt,</i>

1422
01:56:39,553 --> 01:56:42,512
<i>but he couldn't draw that well,
and he didn't have a camera.</i>

1423
01:56:42,597 --> 01:56:46,090
Here, use this one.
Nobody likes that color anyway.

1424
01:56:50,939 --> 01:56:52,601
FORREST: Have a nice day.

1425
01:56:54,234 --> 01:56:55,350
<i>Well, some years later,</i>

1426
01:56:55,444 --> 01:56:59,358
<i>I found out that that man
did come up with an idea for a T-shirt.</i>

1427
01:56:59,448 --> 01:57:01,815
<i>He made a lot of money off of it.</i>

1428
01:57:04,619 --> 01:57:09,034
<i>Anyway, like I was saying,
I had a lot of company.</i>

1429
01:57:10,292 --> 01:57:11,453
<i>My mama always said,</i>

1430
01:57:11,543 --> 01:57:15,958
<i>"You got to put the past behind you
before you can move on."</i>

1431
01:57:17,632 --> 01:57:20,966
<i>And I think that's what
my running was all about.</i>

1432
01:57:21,803 --> 01:57:25,797
<i>I had run for three years, two months,</i>

1433
01:57:26,058 --> 01:57:28,391
<i>14 days and 16 hours.</i>

1434
01:57:44,076 --> 01:57:46,409
Quiet. Quiet.
He's going to say something.

1435
01:57:57,839 --> 01:57:59,580
I'm pretty tired.

1436
01:58:02,427 --> 01:58:04,464
Think I'll go home now.

1437
01:58:23,031 --> 01:58:25,489
Now what are we supposed to do?

1438
01:58:26,451 --> 01:58:30,695
<i>And just like that,
my running days was over.</i>

1439
01:58:32,666 --> 01:58:34,407
<i>So, I went home to Alabama.</i>

1440
01:58:35,210 --> 01:58:39,079
<i>REPORTER: Moments ago, at 2:25 p.m.,
as President Reagan was leaving the...</i>

1441
01:58:39,172 --> 01:58:40,834
<i>(GUNSHOTS FIRING)</i>

1442
01:58:41,133 --> 01:58:45,298
<i>...five or six gunshots were fired
by an unknown would-be assassin.</i>

1443
01:58:45,804 --> 01:58:48,137
<i>The President was shot in the chest,
and the assailant...</i>

1444
01:58:48,223 --> 01:58:50,180
I picked up the mail.

1445
01:58:50,976 --> 01:58:54,811
And one day, out of the blue clear sky,
I got a letter from Jenny,

1446
01:58:54,896 --> 01:58:59,140
wondering if I could come down
to Savannah and see her,

1447
01:58:59,234 --> 01:59:01,817
and that's what I'm doing here.

1448
01:59:01,903 --> 01:59:04,486
She saw me on TV, running.

1449
01:59:04,573 --> 01:59:08,817
I'm supposed to go on the
number nine bus to Richmond Street

1450
01:59:08,910 --> 01:59:15,828
and get off and go one block left
to 1947 Henry Street, Apartment 4.

1451
01:59:15,917 --> 01:59:19,581
Why, you don't need to take a bus.

1452
01:59:19,713 --> 01:59:24,253
Henry Street is just five
or six blocks down that way.

1453
01:59:26,094 --> 01:59:28,427
- Down that way?
- Down that way.

1454
01:59:31,433 --> 01:59:33,345
It was nice talking to you.

1455
01:59:33,602 --> 01:59:34,602
(CAR HORN HONKING)

1456
01:59:34,644 --> 01:59:37,261
I hope everything works out for you!

1457
01:59:44,779 --> 01:59:46,441
Hey!

1458
01:59:46,865 --> 01:59:48,527
Forrest!

1459
01:59:48,783 --> 01:59:52,026
How you doing? Come in, come in!

1460
01:59:52,120 --> 01:59:53,327
I got your letter.

1461
01:59:53,413 --> 01:59:56,030
I was wondering about that.

1462
01:59:57,584 --> 01:59:59,371
Is this your house?

1463
01:59:59,461 --> 02:00:02,545
Yeah. It's messy right now.
I just got off work.

1464
02:00:02,631 --> 02:00:06,341
It's nice. You got air conditioning.

1465
02:00:13,225 --> 02:00:15,262
- Thank you.
- I ate some.

1466
02:00:18,063 --> 02:00:23,479
Hey, I kept a scrapbook
of your clippings and everything.

1467
02:00:23,610 --> 02:00:25,226
There you are.

1468
02:00:26,821 --> 02:00:28,187
And this, I got you running.

1469
02:00:31,159 --> 02:00:33,321
I ran a long way,

1470
02:00:33,828 --> 02:00:35,660
for a long time.

1471
02:00:37,874 --> 02:00:39,365
And there...

1472
02:00:45,882 --> 02:00:49,341
Listen, Forrest,
I don't know how to say this.

1473
02:00:51,846 --> 02:00:56,181
I just I want to apologize
for anything that I ever did to you,

1474
02:00:56,309 --> 02:01:01,555
'cause I was messed up
for a long time, and...

1475
02:01:01,898 --> 02:01:02,898
(KNOCKING AT DOOR)

1476
02:01:03,233 --> 02:01:04,233
Yoo-hoo!

1477
02:01:04,359 --> 02:01:05,975
- Hey.
- Hi.

1478
02:01:06,194 --> 02:01:07,194
Hey, you.

1479
02:01:08,363 --> 02:01:11,322
- This is an old friend from Alabama.
- How do you do?

1480
02:01:11,408 --> 02:01:14,553
JENNY: Listen, next week my schedule
changes, so I'll be able to... But thanks...

1481
02:01:14,577 --> 02:01:16,614
No problem. Got to go, Jen,
I'm double-parked.

1482
02:01:16,705 --> 02:01:18,571
- Okay. Thanks.
- Bye.

1483
02:01:22,043 --> 02:01:24,786
This is my very good friend, Mr. Gump.
Can you say hi to him?

1484
02:01:24,879 --> 02:01:27,963
- Hello, Mr. Gump.
- Hello.

1485
02:01:28,049 --> 02:01:31,042
- Can I go watch TV now?
- Yes, you can. Just keep it low.

1486
02:01:33,888 --> 02:01:37,222
- You're a mama, Jenny.
- I'm a mama.

1487
02:01:40,103 --> 02:01:41,935
His name's Forrest.

1488
02:01:43,064 --> 02:01:44,396
Like me.

1489
02:01:46,026 --> 02:01:48,143
I named him after his daddy.

1490
02:01:49,112 --> 02:01:51,570
He got a daddy named Forrest, too?

1491
02:01:52,866 --> 02:01:54,903
You're his daddy, Forrest.

1492
02:02:09,382 --> 02:02:10,589
Hey.

1493
02:02:11,760 --> 02:02:14,628
Forrest, look at me. Look at me, Forrest.

1494
02:02:17,223 --> 02:02:21,342
There's nothing you need to do, okay?
You didn't do anything wrong.

1495
02:02:21,895 --> 02:02:23,261
Okay?

1496
02:02:27,609 --> 02:02:29,475
Isn't he beautiful?

1497
02:02:30,487 --> 02:02:33,446
He's the most beautiful thing
I've ever seen.

1498
02:02:37,243 --> 02:02:38,324
But...

1499
02:02:41,998 --> 02:02:44,866
Is he smart, or...

1500
02:02:44,959 --> 02:02:48,953
He's very smart.
He's one of the smartest in his class.

1501
02:02:58,306 --> 02:03:00,764
Yeah, it's okay. Go talk to him.

1502
02:03:10,110 --> 02:03:12,944
- What are you watching?
- Bert and Ernie.

1503
02:03:36,052 --> 02:03:37,839
Forrest,

1504
02:03:39,305 --> 02:03:40,841
I'm sick.

1505
02:03:43,518 --> 02:03:47,137
What, do you have
a cough due to a cold?

1506
02:03:47,230 --> 02:03:49,597
I have some kind of virus,

1507
02:03:49,691 --> 02:03:52,399
and the doctors don't...
They don't know what it is,

1508
02:03:52,527 --> 02:03:55,520
and there isn't anything
they can do about it.

1509
02:03:59,909 --> 02:04:02,196
You could come home with me.

1510
02:04:03,872 --> 02:04:09,539
Jenny, you and little Forrest could
come stay at my house in Greenbow.

1511
02:04:13,882 --> 02:04:16,670
I'll take care of you if you're sick.

1512
02:04:19,053 --> 02:04:21,340
Would you marry me, Forrest?

1513
02:04:26,603 --> 02:04:27,844
Okay.

1514
02:04:28,897 --> 02:04:30,559
MINISTER: Please take your seats.

1515
02:04:34,402 --> 02:04:36,735
Forrest? It's time to start.

1516
02:04:56,132 --> 02:04:57,714
Hi.

1517
02:04:58,593 --> 02:05:00,084
Your tie.

1518
02:05:12,649 --> 02:05:14,265
Lieutenant Dan.

1519
02:05:29,624 --> 02:05:31,581
Lieutenant Dan.

1520
02:05:32,418 --> 02:05:34,080
Hello, Forrest.

1521
02:05:34,754 --> 02:05:37,417
You got new legs. New legs!

1522
02:05:38,633 --> 02:05:42,422
Yeah. I got new legs. Custom-made.

1523
02:05:43,137 --> 02:05:47,131
Titanium alloy.
It's what they use on the space shuttle.

1524
02:05:50,979 --> 02:05:52,470
Magic legs.

1525
02:05:54,482 --> 02:05:58,852
This is my fiancÃ©e, Susan.

1526
02:06:01,656 --> 02:06:05,024
- Lieutenant Dan.
- Hi, Forrest.

1527
02:06:07,120 --> 02:06:10,329
Lieutenant Dan, this is my Jenny.

1528
02:06:10,707 --> 02:06:13,700
Hey. It's nice to meet you finally.

1529
02:06:23,845 --> 02:06:28,010
MINISTER: Do you, Forrest,
take Jenny to be your wife?

1530
02:06:29,892 --> 02:06:34,136
Do you, Jenny,
take Forrest to be your husband?

1531
02:06:35,481 --> 02:06:38,849
And so I pronounce you man and wife.

1532
02:07:09,724 --> 02:07:11,590
- Hey.
- Hey.

1533
02:07:25,281 --> 02:07:27,068
Hey, Forrest.

1534
02:07:32,413 --> 02:07:34,200
Were you scared in Vietnam?

1535
02:07:35,875 --> 02:07:38,208
Yes. Well, I...

1536
02:07:39,545 --> 02:07:41,252
I don't know.

1537
02:07:41,964 --> 02:07:46,925
<i>Sometimes it would stop raining long
enough for the stars to come out.</i>

1538
02:07:50,056 --> 02:07:52,093
<i>And then it was nice.</i>

1539
02:07:55,478 --> 02:07:59,438
It was like just before the sun
goes to bed down on the bayou.

1540
02:08:00,733 --> 02:08:04,602
<i>There was always
a million sparkles on the water.</i>

1541
02:08:06,406 --> 02:08:10,320
<i>Like that mountain lake.
It was so clear, Jenny,</i>

1542
02:08:10,451 --> 02:08:15,037
<i>it looked like there were two skies,
one on top of the other.</i>

1543
02:08:17,583 --> 02:08:20,621
And then, in the desert,
when the sun comes up,

1544
02:08:23,089 --> 02:08:27,254
<i>I couldn't tell where heaven stopped</i>

1545
02:08:27,802 --> 02:08:30,169
<i>and the earth began.</i>

1546
02:08:31,431 --> 02:08:33,297
<i>It was so beautiful.</i>

1547
02:08:38,020 --> 02:08:41,104
I wish I could've been there with you.

1548
02:08:44,193 --> 02:08:45,604
You were.

1549
02:08:56,330 --> 02:08:57,787
I love you.

1550
02:09:02,170 --> 02:09:05,504
<i>You died on a Saturday morning.</i>

1551
02:09:07,216 --> 02:09:10,960
And I had you placed
here under our tree.

1552
02:09:15,850 --> 02:09:20,686
And I had that house of your father's
bulldozed to the ground.

1553
02:09:24,817 --> 02:09:26,479
<i>Mama</i>

1554
02:09:27,570 --> 02:09:32,565
always said that dying was a part of life.

1555
02:09:35,995 --> 02:09:38,328
I sure wish it wasn't.

1556
02:09:41,000 --> 02:09:44,744
Little Forrest is doing just fine.

1557
02:09:46,088 --> 02:09:47,169
But...

1558
02:09:47,423 --> 02:09:50,086
<i>About to start school again soon,</i>

1559
02:09:51,928 --> 02:09:55,717
and I make his breakfast, lunch
and dinner every day.

1560
02:09:57,892 --> 02:10:03,889
I make sure he combs his hair
and brushes his teeth every day.

1561
02:10:07,026 --> 02:10:09,609
Teaching him how to play Ping-Pong.

1562
02:10:10,905 --> 02:10:11,941
Okay.

1563
02:10:12,198 --> 02:10:13,359
<i>He's really good.</i>

1564
02:10:13,449 --> 02:10:15,566
Forrest, you go.

1565
02:10:19,789 --> 02:10:21,371
<i>We fish a lot.</i>

1566
02:10:24,919 --> 02:10:28,378
(SOBBING) And every night, we read
a book. He's so smart, Jenny.

1567
02:10:31,634 --> 02:10:33,876
You'd be so proud of him.

1568
02:10:35,596 --> 02:10:37,053
I am.

1569
02:10:38,099 --> 02:10:41,308
He wrote you a letter.

1570
02:10:42,895 --> 02:10:44,932
And he says I can't read it.

1571
02:10:45,064 --> 02:10:48,603
I'm not supposed to,
so I'll just leave it here for you.

1572
02:11:04,667 --> 02:11:05,999
Jenny,

1573
02:11:11,799 --> 02:11:15,008
I don't know if Mama was right,

1574
02:11:16,345 --> 02:11:17,836
or if it's Lieutenant Dan.

1575
02:11:17,972 --> 02:11:20,555
I don't know

1576
02:11:20,641 --> 02:11:25,136
if we each have a destiny,

1577
02:11:27,189 --> 02:11:32,309
or if we're all just floating around
accidental-like on a breeze.

1578
02:11:36,824 --> 02:11:38,656
But I think

1579
02:11:40,536 --> 02:11:42,323
maybe it's both.

1580
02:11:46,667 --> 02:11:49,535
Maybe both is happening
at the same time.

1581
02:11:55,676 --> 02:11:57,668
But I miss you, Jenny.

1582
02:12:04,060 --> 02:12:08,475
If there's anything you need,
I won't be far away.

1583
02:12:43,766 --> 02:12:46,725
Here's your bus. Okay.

1584
02:12:48,396 --> 02:12:51,730
Hey. I know this.

1585
02:12:51,857 --> 02:12:54,725
I'm gonna show that
for show-and-tell because

1586
02:12:54,860 --> 02:12:57,523
Grandma used to read it to you.

1587
02:12:57,613 --> 02:12:59,730
My favorite book.

1588
02:13:03,077 --> 02:13:04,568
Here we are.

1589
02:13:04,745 --> 02:13:06,202
Okay.

1590
02:13:07,915 --> 02:13:09,406
Here you go.

1591
02:13:14,296 --> 02:13:16,788
Hey, Forrest, don't...

1592
02:13:20,261 --> 02:13:23,971
- I wanted to tell you, I love you.
- I love you, too, Daddy.

1593
02:13:25,975 --> 02:13:28,763
I'll be right here when you get back.

1594
02:13:33,315 --> 02:13:36,558
You understand this is
the bus to school, now, don't you?

1595
02:13:36,652 --> 02:13:40,191
Of course, and you are Dorothy Harris,
and I'm Forrest Gump.

